"response_text": "The mean household risk attitude begins at values clustered near zero across all simulation runs. During the initial phase from steps 0 to 20, the metric undergoes rapid divergence, with trajectories spreading across a range from approximately -0.2 to 0.8. This rapid differentiation suggests that learning processes—whether social learning or learning-by-doing—quickly amplify initial variations in household experiences or local conditions into substantially different risk management strategies.\n\nBy step 30, most trajectories have reached temporary plateaus or continue adjusting toward distinct equilibrium levels. A subset of runs stabilizes at high values around 0.7 to 0.8, indicating the development of conservative or highly uncertainty-averse attitudes. Another group stabilizes at moderate positive values between 0.4 and 0.6, while additional trajectories settle at lower positive values between 0.1 and 0.3.\n\nBetween steps 40 and 60, several trajectories exhibit notable declines, with some falling from moderate positive values (around 0.4-0.5) to near zero or negative values (as low as -0.3 to -0.4). These declines suggest episodes where households substantially revise their risk attitudes downward, possibly in response to accumulated experiences of pasture productivity or observed neighbor performance.\n\nAfter step 60, the vast majority of trajectories stabilize with minor fluctuations, maintaining their relative positions until the end of the simulation at step 100. The final values span a wide range from approximately -0.35 to +0.78, indicating persistent heterogeneity in risk attitudes across the simulated populations. This persistent divergence implies that the learning mechanisms in the model create path-dependent outcomes where early stochastic differences become locked into distinct long-term uncertainty management strategies.\n\nThe variability across runs is highest in the middle phase (steps 20-50) and decreases in the final phase as trajectories settle into their respective steady states. This pattern is consistent with an adaptive learning system that explores different behavioral strategies early on before converging on stable risk attitudes suited to specific local ecological and social conditions."
}

